---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const title = "Insurance for International Military Nurses | Compare Expat Plans";
const description = "Health insurance guide for Military Nurses working internationally, covering military nursing transitions abroad, veteran healthcare, and global military nursing careers.";
const headline = "Insurance for International Military Nurses";
const subheadline = "Coverage solutions for Military Nurses working abroad, transitioning to civilian practice internationally, and building careers across military installations, VA facilities, and international healthcare organizations.";
const canonicalPath = "/guides/military-nurse-insurance";
const heroBackgroundImage = "/images/guides/military-nurse-insurance-hero.png";

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', label: 'Overview' },
  { id: 'coverage-needs', label: 'Coverage Needs' },
  { id: 'work-settings', label: 'Work Settings' },
  { id: 'credentials', label: 'Credentials' },
  { id: 'occupational-health', label: 'Occupational Health' },
  { id: 'work-demands', label: 'Work Demands' },
  { id: 'career-considerations', label: 'Career Considerations' },
  { id: 'faqs', label: 'FAQs' },
  { id: 'next-steps', label: 'Next Steps' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title={title}
  description={description}
  headline={headline}
  subheadline={subheadline}
  canonicalPath={canonicalPath}
  heroBackgroundImage={heroBackgroundImage}
  tocItems={tocItems}
>
  <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">

    <section id="overview">
      <h2>International Military Nurse Careers</h2>
      <p>
        Military Nurses serve in armed forces providing healthcare to service members, veterans, and military families. They work in military hospitals, field settings, and deployment zones. Those transitioning to civilian practice bring unique trauma care, leadership, and adaptability skills. This guide addresses both active-duty nurses stationed internationally and military nurses transitioning to international civilian roles.
      </p>
      <p>
        International military nursing careers include overseas duty stations, NATO assignments, and transition to civilian international work. As military nurses separate or retire, their skills are valued in international healthcare settings, humanitarian organizations, and trauma centers worldwide.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide addresses insurance considerations for Military Nurses working abroad across military installations, VA facilities, and international healthcare organizations.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="coverage-needs">
      <h2>Coverage Needs for Military Nurses</h2>

      <ComparisonTable
        columns={[
          { key: 'need', header: 'Coverage Need' },
          { key: 'why', header: 'Why It Matters' },
          { key: 'typical', header: 'Coverage Situation?' },
        ]}
        rows={[
          { need: 'General health coverage', why: 'Professional health maintenance', typical: 'TRICARE while active' },
          { need: 'Mental health support', why: 'Combat trauma and moral injury', typical: 'Usually covered' },
          { need: 'Transition coverage', why: 'Separating from military service', typical: 'Planning needed' },
          { need: 'Preventive care', why: 'Sustaining professional capability', typical: 'Usually covered' },
          { need: 'Service-connected conditions', why: 'Military service impacts', typical: 'VA eligible' },
          { need: 'Travel medical', why: 'International assignments', typical: 'Varies by role' },
        ]}
      />

      <h3>Military to Civilian Transition</h3>
      <p>
        Transitioning from military to civilian practice requires coverage planning. TRICARE ends after separation period. VA eligibility for service-connected conditions. Planning for civilian health coverage essential.
      </p>
      <p>
        Military nurses may have deployment-related health impacts. Combat trauma and PTSD. Physical injuries and exposures. Comprehensive mental health coverage important.
      </p>

      <h3>International Assignment Considerations</h3>
      <p>
        Active-duty overseas assignments covered by TRICARE. Civilian international work requires personal coverage. Understanding coverage gaps essential. Transition planning for international work important.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-settings">
      <h2>Coverage by Work Setting</h2>

      <h3>Active-Duty Military</h3>
      <p>
        Active-duty nurses covered by TRICARE. Overseas duty stations. Deployment assignments. Military provides comprehensive coverage.
      </p>

      <h3>VA Healthcare System</h3>
      <p>
        Veterans Administration employs many military nurses. Federal employee benefits comprehensive. Serving veteran population. VA offers mission continuity.
      </p>

      <h3>Defense Contractor Facilities</h3>
      <p>
        Defense contractors operate overseas healthcare. Contractor benefits vary. Supporting military operations. Contractor work offers overseas opportunities.
      </p>

      <h3>Civilian Trauma Centers</h3>
      <p>
        Civilian trauma centers value military experience. Healthcare employer benefits. Combat casualty skills transfer. Trauma centers utilize military expertise.
      </p>

      <h3>International Humanitarian Work</h3>
      <p>
        Humanitarian organizations value military nursing. International benefits arrangements. Conflict zone experience valuable. Humanitarian work offers global impact.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Coverage for Military Nurses"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for Military Nurses working abroad and transitioning to civilian international practice."
      buttonText="Compare Military Nurse Plans"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

    <section id="credentials">
      <h2>Credentials and Professional Recognition</h2>

      <h3>Nursing Foundation</h3>
      <p>
        Registered Nurse (RN) licensure required. Military nursing education comprehensive. BSN standard for commissioned officers. Military training translates to civilian credentials.
      </p>

      <h3>Military Training Recognition</h3>
      <p>
        Military training recognized by civilian employers. Combat casualty care expertise. Leadership development extensive. Training enhances civilian credentials.
      </p>

      <h3>Specialty Certifications</h3>
      <p>
        Military nurses hold various certifications. CCRN, CEN, TCRN common. Certifications transfer to civilian practice. Maintaining certifications important.
      </p>

      <h3>State Licensure</h3>
      <p>
        State licensure required for civilian practice. Enhanced Nurse Licensure Compact assists. Military spouse licensure provisions. Licensure planning needed for transition.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="occupational-health">
      <h2>Occupational Health Considerations</h2>

      <h3>Combat Trauma Exposure</h3>
      <p>
        Deployment involves trauma exposure. Combat casualties and mass casualty events. PTSD and moral injury risk. Mental health support essential.
      </p>

      <h3>Service-Connected Health</h3>
      <p>
        Military service affects health. Environmental exposures. Physical demands. VA eligibility for service-connected conditions.
      </p>

      <h3>Transition Stress</h3>
      <p>
        Military to civilian transition challenging. Identity and purpose shifts. Family and financial adjustments. Transition support helpful.
      </p>

      <h3>Physical Demands</h3>
      <p>
        Military nursing physically demanding. Field conditions and deployments. Physical fitness requirements. Physical health important.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-demands">
      <h2>Managing Work Demands</h2>

      <h3>Trauma Care</h3>
      <p>
        Combat casualty care expertise. Mass casualty management. Trauma resuscitation skills. Trauma expertise transfers to civilian practice.
      </p>

      <h3>Leadership</h3>
      <p>
        Military nursing develops leadership. Team management and coordination. Decision-making under pressure. Leadership skills valued everywhere.
      </p>

      <h3>Adaptability</h3>
      <p>
        Military nurses adapt to varied settings. Resource-limited environments. Changing missions and locations. Adaptability is core strength.
      </p>

      <h3>Comprehensive Care</h3>
      <p>
        Military nurses provide broad care. Multiple specialty experience. Independent practice skills. Comprehensive training valuable.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="career-considerations">
      <h2>Career Considerations</h2>

      <h3>International Opportunities</h3>
      <p>
        Military experience valued globally. Trauma expertise needed. Humanitarian organizations seek veterans. Coverage must accommodate international practice.
      </p>

      <h3>Career Paths</h3>
      <p>
        Active duty to civilian transition. VA and federal employment. Defense contractor work. Civilian trauma and leadership roles.
      </p>

      <h3>Credential Portability</h3>
      <p>
        Military training recognized globally. Nursing credentials transfer. Specialty certifications valid. Military experience respected internationally.
      </p>

      <h3>Career Longevity</h3>
      <p>
        Military nursing offers unique career path. Retirement benefits for career service. Civilian careers after military. Multiple career stages possible.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="faqs">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I'm a military nurse considering international civilian work. What should I know?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Military nursing experience valued globally. Transition requires coverage planning. Skills highly transferable. Coverage should accommodate your work location.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">How does TRICARE work internationally?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            TRICARE covers active duty overseas. Overseas Prime and Select options. Coverage varies by region. Understanding benefits important.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">What about coverage after separation?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            TRICARE transitional coverage available. VA for service-connected conditions. Civilian health coverage needed. Transition planning essential.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Will my military nursing credentials transfer?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Military nursing training recognized globally. Certifications transfer. State licensure needed for US civilian practice. Military experience valued.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">What about deployment-related health conditions?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            VA covers service-connected conditions. Combat trauma and PTSD treatment. Environmental exposure evaluation. VA eligibility important benefit.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">What civilian roles utilize military experience?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Trauma centers and emergency departments. Leadership and management roles. Humanitarian organizations. Defense contractors. Multiple opportunities exist.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="next-steps">
      <h2>Next Steps</h2>
      <p>
        Start by understanding your current and future coverage situation. Active duty covered by TRICARE. Transition requires coverage planning. VA eligibility for veterans. International civilian work requires personal coverage attention.
      </p>
      <p>
        Military nurses bring exceptional trauma care, leadership, and adaptability to healthcare. Your coverage should support your service and transitions—addressing combat-related health needs, enabling international practice, and protecting your health through military and civilian nursing careers.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Protect Your Military Nursing Career"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for Military Nurses working abroad and transitioning to civilian international practice."
      buttonText="Compare Plans Now"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

  </article>
</PageShell>
